funding_code: ECONOMIC IMPACT INITIATIVE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist with the costs associated with the purchase of a new dump truck with plow and spreader. This vehicle is needed to replace the towns maintenance vehicle which is over 30 years old and has reached the end of its useful life. Their current vehicles under body has rusted through and is a safety concern for the towns operator. Additionally, it is a 2-wheel drive vehicle which is unreliable and does not perform well on the mountainous, hilly roads especially during inclement weather. The new vehicle will be 4 wheel drive and better equipped to serve the town by clearing roads during winter months and for trash removal services.

funding_code: ECONOMIC IMPACT INITIATIVE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Other Services (except Public Administration) (81)
naics_description: COMMERCIAL AND INDUSTRIAL MACHINERY AND EQUIPMENT (EXCEPT AUTOMOTIVE AND ELECTRONIC) REPAIR AND MAINTENANCE
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist with the purchase of public works equipment. The town of Luke experienced the closing of VERSO plant which provided the town with access to water and sewer. As the town transitions to support their own water and sewer and public works department they are faced with inadequate confined spaces access and equipment to maintain their municipal infrastructure. The town is proposing to purchase equipment to support safe confined spaces access and maintenance of the municipal public works facilities.

funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Wholesale Trade (42)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development Investment will be used to replace fire fighting equipment for the Barton Hose Company. The equipment it intends to purchase include an Arc Cascade System, eight self contained breathing apparatuses (SCBA) Air Pac Bottles, three Thermal Image Cameras, and Air Bags for Auto Extraction. This organization has been providing fire suppression and public safety services to this very small town and rural county for over 100 years. The population of Barton is only 441, and the median household income is $44,688, which is less than 60% of the state non-metropolitan median household income.

funding_code: (GRANT ONLY) ECWAG - APPROPRIATED $150,000 LIMIT
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to replace a portion of the ductile iron pipe and fittings which have deteriorated as a result of the acidity level of the soils. This line connects the county water district to the city of Frostburgs system, the water supplier, at State Route 55. Due to the acidic soils in the area, the water district has been losing approximately 25 percent of its purchased water for several years due to line leaks and breakages. Once completed, the improvements will reduce breaks, leaks, and ultimately the amount of lost water in the system. This is a water service to approximately 100 homes and currently provides an emergency connection to the town of Lonaconings water distribution system in Midland, Maryland.

funding_code: (GRANT ONLY) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to replace water distribution lines throughout the town of Luke. The current lines at the end of their useful life are in need of constant repair and have created a potential health and sanitary issue. By replacing these lines, the towns 56 residents will have reliable delivery of safe, potable drinking water.

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
naics_description: REGULATION OF AGRICULTURAL MARKETING AND COMMODITIES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to establish a business support center to assist with COVID-19 pandemic recovery efforts for the recreational riding industry through promotion and marketing for Marylands new major recreational riding event. The project will support the development of small and emerging private business enterprises in rural areas of five Maryland counties including Cecil, Queen Annes, Caroline, Garrett, and Allegany. Successful marketing and expansion will result in supporting and creating new jobs.

funding_code: REAP-MANDATORY RENEW ENERGY SYST GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
naics_description: BROILERS AND OTHER MEAT TYPE CHICKEN PRODUCTION
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used for the purchase and installation of a 321.9 kW solar array. Beyla Farm grows chickens for the integrator Mountaire Farms. They also grow organic grain and hay. Beyla Farms will realize $35,120 per year in savings and will replace 411,040 kWh (107 percent) per year. This project will save enough electricity to power 37 homes.

program: Rural Energy for America Program Renewable Energy Systems and Energy Efficiency Improvement Loans and Grants
funding_code: REAP-MANDATORY RENEW ENERGY SYST GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase and install a 323.76 kilowatt solar array for Better Days Farm. This family owned poultry farming business will save $26,029 per year and replace 427,000 kilowatt hours (100%) per year. This project will save enough electricity to power 39 homes.

funding_code: MAND. RENEW ENERFY SYSTEMS GRANTS UNDER $20,000
naics_industry_sector: Retail Trade (44-45)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase and install a solar array. This project is expected to save the business $4,35 in electrical costs per year.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase and install a solar array. Race Pace Bicycles is locally operated and its beginnings trace back to 1978. The Westminster, Maryland location of Race Pace Bicycles, has been in business since 1990. This project is expected to save the business $3,403 in electrical costs per year.

funding_code: LAMP BEGINNING AND SOCIALLY DISADVANTAGED FARMERS OR RANCHERS GRANTS - COVID
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to upgrade packaging and expand sales of the farms free-range eggs. The Willet Family Farm is a diversified farm that grows vegetables, flowers, hay, raises laying hens for free-range eggs, and has a small cattle herd for grass-fed beef. The farm is also an agritourism destination with one private campsite that can host groups of up to six people, has walking trails and a restored barn that is rented out for events and church services. The activities of this grant application are aimed at approximately doubling the customer base from a current baseline of 950 over the two year grant period. This increase to 2,300 customers per year (4,050 over the two year grant period) will be the result of enhancing the labelling (to market as local and free range) and promoting the farms eggs to the local market through advertising and agritourism channels.

funding_code: (WWA PROGRAM AREA) TAT GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to host (1) comprehensive training for each of the five listed service areas to provide community leaders, NGOs, government officials, and wastewater professionals with the basic knowledge and direct technical assistance to solve local wastewater pollution issues, (2) complete a 2-3 page memo detailing the problems and solutions discussed during each training, along with a table of identified funding sources and their various requirements, eligibility, due dates, etc. to be sent to participants within a month after the training, (3) offer subsequent trainings as a "deeper dive" for wastewater professionals (e.g. engineers, contractors) into the technical aspects of approved secondary or tertiary green infrastructure wastewater treatment methods, (4) compile a list of wastewater professionals interested in pursuing further training in green infrastructure solutions such that the project team can provide them with or refer them to relevant training programs, (5) film the construction of a Bioreactor Garden for use in future certification programs, and (6) complete at least two demonstration and community restoration projects with existing in-hand funding.

funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide funding to support the connection of Fire Station 16 to the town of Perryville municipal water system. This will include a connection to their fire house building from the town of Perryvilles nearby water main infrastructure situated in Perryville Travel Plaza. Station 16 has two wells which have failed due to contamination. Maryland Department of the Environment (MDE) has provided funding in the amount of $140,000. The connection of municipal water will allow Fire Station 16 to have potable water. This fire station is located in Cecil County and provides fire and rescue services for the town and surrounding area.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development Investment will be used to replace a 1962 well and improve a community water distribution system in order to provide safe, clean and affordable drinking water. The system serves a small community of 16 single-family residences in the unincorporated area of Charles County. In December 2020, the communitys well failed and residents had to rely on purchasing tanker water as a source of drinking water. This project received additional funding from SERCAP, which provided a grant of $20,000 to help purchase temporary water.

program: Rural Energy for America Program Renewable Energy Systems and Energy Efficiency Improvement Loans and Grants
funding_code: REAP-MANDATORY RENEW ENERGY SYST GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Transportation and Warehousing (48-49)
naics_description: ALL OTHER SUPPORT ACTIVITIES FOR TRANSPORTATION
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase and install a 94.4 kilowatt solar array for Warwick Fulfillment Solutions, an e-commerce fulfillment center who ship products to customers of their clients companies. Warwick Fulfillment Solutions will save $12,540 per year and replace 111,966 kilowatt hours (76%) per year. This project will save enough electricity to power 10 homes.

funding_code: ECONOMIC IMPACT INITIATIVE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Wholesale Trade (42)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase essential rescue equipment for the Hurlock Volunteer Fire Company. The fire company provides essential firefighting, EMS, and rescue services to not only the rural town of Hurlock, but also other surrounding communities such as East New Market, Secretary, and Cambridge. The equipment to-be-purchased includes an inclined cutter, spreader, ram, scene lights, exhaust fans, and pagers. The new, more efficient, battery-operated equipment, will replace outdated hydraulic rescue tools currently being used. The new rescue equipment will allow for the operation of a safer, more efficient, emergency scene, and benefit both first responders and citizens alike.

naics_description: OTHER FOOD CROPS GROWN UNDER COVER

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to support the development of small and emerging businesses from rural areas in Frederick County and surrounding rural communities. Frederick Innovative Technology Center helps entrepreneurs achieve success by encouraging technological innovation and accelerating the development of commercially viable technology-based entities. The project will fund the expansion of Frederick Innovative Technology Centers entrepreneurial program therefore resulting in direct development and financing of its startup companies.

funding_code: VALUE-ADDED PRODUCER DVLP GRANTS-DISCR
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
naics_description: OTHER FOOD CROPS GROWN UNDER COVER
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to expand District Farms, LLCs current hydroponically grown lettuce operation through a detailed marketing and sales endeavor. The anticipated result will increase revenue from $1.5 million in 2021 to $9.5 million by 2023. There will be a focus on a new customer base in Maryland for same day delivery of fresh produce to local stores.

funding_code: LOCAL AGRICULTURE MARKET RESOURCE PROGRAM (LAMP) VALUE-ADDED PRODUCER GRANTS - COVID
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to professionalize, strengthen and expand Moon Valley Farms marketing reach, grow the business, and further diversify income streams. This project will professionalize marketing by employing graphic designers, videographers, and new experienced staff members to create a new website to stimulate lead generation, customer acquisition and customer support. The Farm will use funding from this project to expand the current sales outlets, growing the CSA membership from 550 to 800 people within 2 years, and the number of restaurants they sell to from 50 to 75. The project also includes creation of wholesale accounts as a new market outlet, with a goal of establishing four new accounts over the two-year timeframe. Additionally, this project will expand sales to include a third city, Frederick, MD, which will add over one hundred direct market customers and grow gross sales by over $300,000 from this city alone.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Construction (23)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a new backhoe, tractor, work truck, and computer equipment to be used by the towns public works department. The new equipment will continue to provide road maintenance in all seasons, wastewater treatment services and water service to its residents and businesses. The multi-use tractor, truck and backhoe will be used to provide snow removal, road maintenance and repair water leaks. The new computer equipment will be used at the wastewater treatment plant to prevent security vulnerability and hacking to the facility equipment.

funding_code: SECD RB DEV ENTERPRISE GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
naics_description: ADMINISTRATION OF URBAN PLANNING AND COMMUNITY AND RURAL DEVELOPMENT
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to support the continued development of $MART ART: Shared Workspace, a rural incubator space located in the Oakland Arts & Entertainment District, Garrett County, Maryland. GCACs proposal develops a rural business incubator space, an ADA- accessible community workspace equipped with various digital, traditional tools and services assisting rural art entrepreneurs (visual artists, performing artists, writers and culinary artists/producers/farmers) to flourish in the global digital-based economy.

borrower_name: OAKLAND,  MAYOR AND TOWN COUNCIL OF
funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist with the costs associated with the purchase of a new police vehicle. The vehicle will be a SUV police cruiser, complete with new operations radio equipment, new computer equipment, complete with in-car video cameras, necessary storage box and equipment as well as safety barrier, etc. This will improve the Departments ability to safely perform necessary public safety and efficient police work.

borrower_name: OAKLAND,  MAYOR AND TOWN COUNCIL OF
funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
naics_description: OTHER PUBLIC BUILDING & IMPROVEMENT RELATED SERVICES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist with the costs associated with the purchase of public works vehicles. Their current vehicles are limited and aging with many nearing the end of their useful life. The vehicle that is to be replaced has become obsolete from normal wear and tear over the years and has also suffered technological obsolescence due to its age and can only provide a reduced ability to provide for the Towns public safety needs. This is for the Town of Oakland with a population of 1,925.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development Investment will be used to improve the Grantsville sewer system. These improvements include addressing infiltration, inflow, and spikes in flow that correspond with rain events. Funding also includes the completion of a full I/I study consisting of flow monitoring, detailed manhole inspections, manhole monitoring during rain events, smoke testing and CCTV.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development Investment will be used to improve the Grantsville sewer system. These improvements include addressing infiltration, inflow, and spikes in flow that correspond with rain events. Funding also includes the completion of a full I/I study consisting of flow monitoring, detailed manhole inspections, manhole monitoring during rain events, smoke testing and CCTV.

funding_code: (GRANT ONLY) PRE-DEVELOPMENT GRANTS - WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help fund the development of a Preliminary Engineering Report and Environmental Report required to address Maryland Department of the Environments (MDE) concerns regarding the vulnerability of their water sources. MDE is suggesting that the Sanitary District find other options for intake water sources. The water system has issues with filtration, pathogens and organic contaminants. This project will support water system needs for the Town of Friendsville in Garret County, Maryland.

funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development Investment will be used to improve a mental health facility that provides services to clients and office space for staff of Key Point Health Services Inc by waterproofing the basement walls in an effort to protect medical records and prevent potential health concerns for clients and staff. The organization is a 501 (c) (3) non-profit corporation that serves adults and children. Key Point has been providing community based mental health services since 1983 and will be contributing $37,100 to this project. The organization is an existing USDA borrower and, since 2005, has operated from 135 North Parke Street, Aberdeen, MD. This property, and two adjoining properties, were purchased in September 2015 with proceeds from a $5,000,000 Community Facilities loan. The population benefiting from this project is traditionally under-served, low-income individuals, who rely on medical assistance as their primary means for mental health services. The project area has a median household income of $47, 868, which is less than 60% of the State Median Household Income. This project is critical to the effort to sustain the level of care Key Point Health Services is providing to the community.

funding_code: RCDI RURAL COMMUNITY DEVELOPMENT INITIATIVE GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to support the Rural Housing Production and Preservation Capacity Cohorts program that helps non-profit recipients acquire RD, HUD, LIHTC and other subsidized housing nationwide. Enterprise Community Partners, Inc. accomplishes this goal by a combination of direct training, peer learning, and direct technical assistance. This work supports efforts to preserve this critically limited housing stock that benefits low-income rural residents across the country. The thirteen non-profits that will benefit as recipients are: Bogalusa Rebirth, In Bogalusa, LA; Catholic Charities in Wapato, WA; Catholic Charities in Wenactchee, WA; Farmworker Housing Development Corporation in Woodburn, OR; Helping One Another, Inc. in Sardis, MS; Kenai Peninsula Housing in Homer, AK; San Luis Valley Housing Coalition in Alamosa, CO; Tunica County Community Development Coalition, Inc. in Ponchatoula, LA; Northwest Coastal Housing in Newport, OR; Neighbor Works in Roseburg, OR; MS Center for Police and Sheriffs in Bogalusa, LA; Project Build a Future in Raymond, MS; and Tangi Community Development in Lake Charles, LA. This funding will augment the funding from last fiscal year.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a new mower and trailer for the Town of Rock Halls landscaping operations. funding_code: COMMUNITY CONNECTIVITY-ORIENTED GTS
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct a 17 mile Fiber-to-the Premises system to benefit 130 residents and 1business in the Talbot County, Maryland service area. Subscribers will have access to service up to 1 Gbps, expanding access to economic, educational, health care, and public safety opportunities. A community center will be provided in a pre-fabricatedbuilding placed as part of this projectwhere residents can access the Internet free of charge for at least two years.

funding_code: DISTANCE LEARNING- GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to expand its synchronous distance learning opportunities by purchasing distance learning technologies, specifically video endpoints and display systems that will broadcast the class and enable interactivity. An advisory council of Chesapeake College academic and enrollment administrators, library directors, and a representative from the Upper Shore Workforce Investment Board will meet prior to each academic year to assess the education and training needs within each community served by the above sites. That assessment will drive the synchronous distance learning opportunities that will be available at each site.

funding_code: B&I CORONAVIRUS AID, RELIEF AND ECONOMIC SECURITY ACT GUARANTEED LOANS
naics_industry_sector: Accommodation and Food Services (72)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide Shore United Bank with a loan guarantee for their loan to Asiya Hospitality LLC for working capital needs related to the COVID-19 pandemic impacts to the business. The borrower also received assistance through the Small Business Administration totaling $81,800 for other working capital expenses for payroll purposes. Asiya Hospitality LLC was founded in 2017 in conjunction with the purchase of the Holiday Inn Express, in Easton MD. This small business has 24 employees.

program: Rural Energy for America Program Renewable Energy Systems and Energy Efficiency Improvement Loans and Grants
funding_code: REAP-MANDATORY RENEW ENERGY SYST GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Arts, Entertainment, and Recreation (71)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase and install a 40.5 kilowatt solar array for Callahan Horse Training and Breakaway Racing, a training and horse racing business that will save $7,520 per year and replace 53,402 kilowatt hours (100%) per year. This project will save enough electricity to power five homes.

funding_code: DISCRETION ASSIST MICROPENTERPRENUERS
naics_industry_sector: Other Services (except Public Administration) (81)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide business based training and technical assistance to rural microenterprises and microentrepreneurs on the Eastern Shore of Maryland. As a participating microlender, grant funds are made available to Eastern Shore Entrepreneurship Center annually based on lending activity and the availability of funding. Previous grant funds have supported this project, and been matched with at least 15% from Eastern Shore Entrepreneurship Center.

funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Other Services (except Public Administration) (81)
naics_description: COMMERCIAL AND INDUSTRIAL MACHINERY AND EQUIPMENT (EXCEPT AUTOMOTIVE AND ELECTRONIC) REPAIR AND MAINTENANCE
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a police truck and public works utility body pick up truck equipped to support a snow plow. Both vehicles proposed to be purchased will provide public safety support for the town. This is their first Community Facility Grant. The town is a coastal community located on Marylands Eastern Shore adjacent to the Chesapeake Bay. Their median household income (MHI) is $58,750 and is 73.17 percent of the State MHI. Their population is 651. This is a truly rural community providing essential services for their municipality.

funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural development investment will be used to replace the belt filter press and pump at the Region II Wastewater Treatment Plant located in Talbot County, Maryland. The ability to completely dry the sludge will result in increased processing efficiency at the plant and eliminate the need to have the unprocessed sludge sent off-site for treatment, which resulted in additional costs for hauling and disposal.

funding_code: (GRANT ONLY) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to fund the additional engineering and project cost incurred for the added scope of the project for the removal of sludge. The project provided the upgrade of the Oxford Wastewater Treatment plant and included the treatment for biological nutrient removal and enhanced nutrient removal, thereby minimizing the impact on the Chesapeake Bay. The wastewater treatment plant serves the Town of Oxford, with a population of 651, in Talbot County, Maryland.

funding_code: LAMP VALUE ADDED PRODUCER GRANT MANDATORY
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help Diparma Farms, a veteran and family-owned farm, expand their free-range poultry operations. The working capital grant funds will be used to pay eligible operating costs directly related to the processing and marketing of their packaged free-range chicken, duck, and turkey products. The project focuses on a planned customer expansion in partnership with local beef and cheese producers throughout Washington county and surrounding areas. Diparma Farms anticipates increased revenue because of the project.

funding_code: LAMP VALUE ADDED PRODUCER GRANT MANDATORY
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help Rohrersville Vineyards LLC dba Big Cork Vineyards expand their existing winery business. The working capital grant will be used to pay eligible operating costs directly related to the processing and marketing of their bottled wines. The revenue from retail wine is expected to double and the revenue from wine membership is expected to increase by one and a half times.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Wholesale Trade (42)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to support the purchase a a snowplow and ten thermal imaging cameras (TICs). The snowplow will be the "V" blade design which allows snow to be pushed away from both sides of the vehicle and the new TICs will allow HFC to equip more firefighters with this live saving technology. The project is located in Washington County, Maryland and their service area is part of the disaster designation FEMA-4374-DR, Maryland Disaster Declaration as of 6/25/18, Maryland Severe Storms and Flooding. The project has been determined to be cost effective and is providing leveraging of funding at a minimum of 25% or the maximum amount needed to fully fund the project and funding regulations for the Community Facility program. The area to be served is truly rural in nature and has a median household income of $31,858 which is 39.68 percent of the State Median Household Income of $80,289. Population of the facility location is 1,545.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Construction (23)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a new garbage truck for the sanitation department. The proposed equipment will replace the towns current truck that is no longer operable.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Construction (23)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a new dump truck, excavator, and patrol vehicle. The proposed equipment will replace equipment that is past its useful life. The dump truck and excavator will be used for street repair, asphalt repair, water mains and sewer line maintenance. The patrol vehicle will be used to provide public safety to the town and neighboring jurisdictions.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
naics_description: RESCUE AND AMBULANCE SERVICE - EQUIPMENT BUILDING
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a new emergency medical services (EMS) vehicle. The proposed vehicle will replace SVFCs 2005 EMS unit which has become unsafe, unreliable, and too expensive to maintain. The vehicle will be used to deploy trained personnel to incident locations in order to provide patient care, assess actual scene conditions, and organize arriving and needed resources. Without RD assistance, the fire company would be forced to wait an additional 2-3 years to obtain a new EMS vehicle, which would negatively impact the level of public safety that the fire company would be able to provide to the community.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a pumper truck. The truck will be custom built and designed for the local topography, mission, and response types.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Construction (23)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a street sweeper to be used by the street department. The Town also plans to use funds to purchase maintenance equipment to ensure that the sweeper runs in peak condition for years to come. The proposed equipment is needed to replace equipment that has been outdated for some time and is no longer able to be repaired and brought back to working order again. All service on cleaning streets has been suspended until the town can purchase new equipment. This street sweeper will help maintain requirements for MS4, WHIP, and Chesapeake Runoff program as well as maintain a clean appearance for the community.

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Educational Services (61)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to develop and implement an Eastern Shore Rural Business Recovery and Resiliency Program to provide consulting, training, and technical assistance services to small business clients in rural counties on the Eastern Shore of Maryland. This will include Kent, Queen Annes, Talbot, Caroline, Dorchester, Wicomico, Somerset and Worcester counties. The project will support the development of small and emerging private business enterprises in rural areas with a focus on businesses impacted by the COVID-19 pandemic.

funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to rehabilitate four obsolete pump stations in Pocomoke City, located in rural Worcester County. The upgrades will consist of converting the four underground pump station structures into wet wells and installing submersible pumps, rails, valves, and controls. The proposed project will benefit the residents of Pocomoke City by ensuring continuous sanitary sewer system function. In addition, the upgrades would help to facilitate reasonable and planned economic growth in the area, while also helping to protect the Chesapeake Bay watershed.

funding_code: (GRANT ONLY) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to extend sanitary sewer service to the area of Lewis Road in rural Berlin, located in Worcester County, Md. The proposed project will be an extension of the Worcester County "Landings" sewer service area. Both local residents and the environment will benefit as this will alleviate the health and sanitary problems currently caused by failing septic systems. The proposed project will consist of constructing a gravity sewer collection system with a central grinder pump station to connect 46 residential and three commercial users to the existing Landings Wastewater Treatment Plant.

funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Wholesale Trade (42)
project_announced_description: This rural development investment will be used to purchase a Tahoe Emergency Medical Service (EMS) response vehicle and lighting package. Orleans Volunteer Fire Companys (OVFC) current EMS response vehicle is a 1998 Chevy Suburban. It is nearly 25 years old and was donated to OVFC by another fire company who retired it from their fleet several years ago. The vehicle has very high mileage, and it is no longer financially feasible to make repairs to a vehicle of that age and mileage. The area to be served is truly rural in nature and has a median household income of $40,301 which is 50.19 percent of the State Median Household Income of $80,289.

funding_code: (GRANT ONLY) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide additional funding to support the towns replacement of their entire sewer system. The Town of Luke operates and maintains the sewer collection system for their residents. The sewer system was constructed by a former paper mill located within the town and consists of terra cotta pipe, a few man holes, a pump station and force main, as well as a grinder pump and force main. Sewage is conveyed to the Upper Potomac River Commission Westernport Waste Water Treatment Plant. The sewer collection system is in need of replacement and is being completed in phases. This project is funding Phase 3 and includes the replacement of the existing gravity sewer in the Mullen Avenue area. The service area population, per 2010 Census is 65 with a MHI of $17,500, (21.80%) and is below 80% of the SNMHI at $80,289. Maryland Department of the Environment is providing funding for this project in the amount of $506,000.

funding_code: HIGHER BLENDS INFRASTRUCTURE INCENTIVE PROGRAM GRANTS - MANDATORY
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to create infrastructure to expand the sales and use of renewable fuels. Royal Farms is the owner of 10 or more fueling stations. This project will install 110 dispensers at 17 fueling stations located in Maryland and Delaware. Stations locations impacted by this grant are: Hanover, Hyattville, Upper Malboro, Pikesville, Frederick, Catonsville, White Marsh, Baltimore, Glen Burnie, Windsor Mill, Capital Heights, Odenton, in Maryland and Bear, Del. This project aims to increase the amount of ethanol sold by 40,077,000 gallons per year.

program: Rural Energy for America Program Renewable Energy Systems and Energy Efficiency Improvement Loans and Grants
funding_code: REAP-MANDATORY RENEW ENERGY SYST GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
naics_description: BROILERS AND OTHER MEAT TYPE CHICKEN PRODUCTION
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help Randy Collins, who owns a poultry farm in Federalsburg, Maryland, purchase and install a 83.52 kW ground mounted solar system. The system is expected to save the farm $15,681 in electrical costs per year and replace 112,105 kilowatt hours (kWh) (82.26 percent of the companys energy use) per year, which is enough energy to power 10 homes.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
naics_description: CONTINUING CARE RETIREMENT COMMUNITIES AND ASSISTED LIVING FACILITIES FOR THE ELDERLY
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to create a more resilient and sustainable regional food system by partnering with Chesapeake Culinary Center for the establishment of Eastern Shore Delmarva Farm to Freezer project; a produce processing and aggregation facility. The Farm to Freezer Facility aims to solve a number of problems in the region, including increasing the availability of locally processed produce, especially to areas of the Eastern Shore having limited access; creating increased revenue and profit margin opportunities for local farmers and growers by providing wider access to different markets; and creating the opportunity for growers to scale and diversify their production and increase employment. The facility will occupy 5,000 square feet, with half the space used for processing and Individual Quick Frozen equipment and the other half set aside for refrigerated, freezer, and dry storage and staging for shipping and receiving. The community served by this project includes several counties on the Eastern Shore Caroline, Dorchester, Kent, Queen Annes, Somerset, Talbot, Wicomico, and Worcester where the estimated poverty rate is over 13 percent and access to nutritious food is limited.

program: Rural Energy for America Program Renewable Energy Systems and Energy Efficiency Improvement Loans and Grants
funding_code: REAP-MANDATORY RENEW ENERGY SYST GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Administrative and Support and Waste Management and Remediation Services (56)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development Investment will be used to help Eagle Transfer Services Inc. purchase and install a 63 kilowatt (kW) ground mounted solar system. Eagle Transfer Services is a trash removal business in Finksburg, Maryland. The new system is expected to save the company $9,201 in electrical costs per year. It will replace 70,778 kilowatt hours (kWh) (109 percent of the companys energy use) per year, which is enough energy to power six homes.

program: Rural Energy for America Program Renewable Energy Systems and Energy Efficiency Improvement Loans and Grants
funding_code: REAP-MANDATORY RENEW ENERGY SYST GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help Dell Brothers Inc. purchase and install a 203 kilowatt (kW) roof mounted solar system. Dell Brothers Inc. is a family-owned grain farm in Westminster, Maryland. The new system is expected to save the farm $24,700 in electrical costs per year. It will replace 249,060 kilowatt hours (kWh) (121 percent of the companys energy use) per year, which is enough energy to power 23 homes.

program: Rural Energy for America Program Renewable Energy Systems and Energy Efficiency Improvement Loans and Grants
funding_code: REAP-MANDATORY RENEW ENERGY SYST GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help Baugher Enterprise purchase and install a 773 kilowatt (kW) ground mounted solar system. Baugher Enterprise is a family-owned fruit and vegetable orchard in Westminster, Maryland. The new system is expected to save the farm $132,883 in electrical costs per year and replace 1,107,360 kilowatt hours (kWh) (94.3 percent of the companys energy use) per year, which is enough energy to power 102 homes.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to support Westminster Rescue Missions Addiction Healing Center (AHC) and better prepare and equip the staff and facility to handle the COVID-19 pandemic. This support includes broadened access to COVID-19 testing and vaccination, better preparation for an influx of individuals seeking Substance Use Disorder Treatment, and better support for the AHC clients. With COVID-19 playing a huge part in the opioid crisis, AHC is providing double the treatment, leading to the need for additional staffing. The center plans to hire a nurse practitioner, peer recovery coordinator, and client care coordinator. Drug and alcohol use has increased during the pandemic, but the number of people seeking treatment decreased with the fear of exposure to COVID-19. WRM will be able to treat these patients in all areas with the additional staff to support the ongoing efforts to combat this pandemic.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to upgrade the Westminster Rescue Missions current facility by paving out three different areas of the campus to enable better flow of cars for the increase in patrons due to COVID-19. The facility will upgrade its refrigeration, security measure- key-less entry and outside lighting. The facility is currently functioning as a food distribution center but seeks to improve the campus based on the increase in patrons due to COVID-19 pandemic. The result of this investment will deliver safe and secure road ways and parking areas for the larger vehicles delivering larger quantities of food.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
naics_description: ASSISTED LIVING FACILITIES FOR THE ELDERLY
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to reimburse Christiana Health Care Services Inc. for staffing and supply expenses incurred directly related to the effects of COVID-19 pandemic. Since the start of the pandemic ChristianaCare Union Hospital has proven its role as a community anchor, providing extraordinary care as the virus spread across Cecil County, Maryland. ChristianaCare Union Hospital responded quickly in acquiring staffing and supplies to meet the needs of the community. The initial investment purchased in labor, lab equipment, equipment for vaccines, ventilators, and testing supplies allowed them to meet the needs of the increased patient volume. This project will allow ChristianaCare Union Hospital to continue to serve those of Elkton, Maryland most effectively.

borrower_name: END HUNGER IN CHARLES COUNTY, MARYLAND, INC.
funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to expand End Hungers services in partnership with Indian Head Grocery Initiative and Mancuso Foods by establishing a food distribution facility in Indian Head, Maryland., in response to the COVID-19 pandemic. This project addresses food insecurity to allow residents to benefit from a food distribution facility in collaboration with an up-and-coming grocery store, Mancuso Foods, and local food pantries. End Hunger plans to use grant funds to invest in a vacant building, purchase two refrigerated trucks to help with deliveries, develop walk-in freezers and refrigerators, and also purchase bulk food. The result of this investment will increase food supply in Indian Head, population 3,844 with over 12 percent living in poverty. The community has not had a fresh food source since 1999. The expansion of End Hunger will result in food access to low income families, increase job opportunities, and better serve the community.

This project has a total of 18 one-bedroom, 30 two-bedroom and 24 three-bedroom units housed in four walk-up three-story residential buildings.

funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to make sewer system improvements. The project will replace the Modified Ludzack-Ettinger (MLE) treatment process system with the Simultaneous Nitrification and Denitrification (SNDN) process in the existing waste water treatment Modules No. 2. This project also includes the construction of a tertiary clarifier and refurbish the aerobic digester, and force main construction work.

funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to make sewer system improvements. This project includes the construction of a central regional pumping station, installation of a 24-inch sewer line to the La Plata Waste Water Treatment Plant and along additional town roadways. The project will also replace the existing Modified Ludzack-Ettinger (MLE) treatment process system with the Simultaneous Nitrification and Denitrification (SNDN) process in the existing wastewater treatment Modules No. 1 and expand the treatment process reactor to where the equalization and digester reactors are in the current layout.

funding_code: (GRANT ONLY) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide additional funding for the upgrade of the Twin Cities waste water treatment plant, which serves the rural communities, in and surrounding, the towns of Secretary and East New Market, which are located in Dorchester County, Maryland.The proposed project would provide an enhanced nutrient removal system for the facility. This facility is past its useful life and requires an upgrade to meet current National Pollutant Discharge Elimination System requirements. This project will address health and sanitary concerns related to the effluent discharged into the Warwick River would be alleviated. The Warwick River flows into the Choptank River, a major tributary of the Chesapeake Bay. The upgrade will ensure sanitary sewer service for approximately 1300 rural residents and facilitate reasonable and planned growth in these communities. The project will also contribute to the support of environmental protection initiatives. USDA funding is being leveraged through funding provided from the Maryland Department of the Environment and Dorchester County.

funding_code: RCDI RURAL COMMUNITY DEVELOPMENT INITIATIVE GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to support the Rural Housing Production and Preservation Capacity Cohorts program that helps non-profit recipients acquire Rural Development, Housing and Urban Development, Low Income Housing Tax Credit and other subsidized housing nationwide. Enterprise Community Partners, Inc. accomplishes this goal by a combination of direct training, peer learning, and direct technical assistance. This work supports efforts to preserve this critically limited housing stock that benefits low-income rural residents across the country, specifically Native Homeownership Coalitions. The 14 non-profits that will benefit as recipients are: Blackfoot Housing Authority, Browning, Montana; Four Bands, Eagle Butte, South Dakota; The Lakota Fund Incorporated, Kyle, South Dakota; Mazaska Owecaso Otipi Financial, Inc, Pine Ridge, South Dakota; Montana Native Growth Fund, Hays, Montana; Northern Cheyenne Housing Authority, Lame Deer, Montana; OSTPH, Allen, South Dakota; Jemez of Pueblo, Jemez Pueblo, New Mexico; Salish Kootenai Housing Authority, Pablo, Montana; Shashone Bannock Tribe, Fort Hall, Idaho; Sicangu Housing, Rosebud, South Dakota; Sisseton Wahpeton Housing Authority, Agency Village, South Dakota; Tatanka Funds, Mission, South Dakota; Tiwa Lending Service, Isleta Pueblo, New Mexico

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to fund Minarys Dream Alliances Feed the Elderly food distribution program for senior low-income residents of Kent County, Maryland. Funded categories will include five part time staff, food and packaging supplies, equipment, and travel expenses. The Feed the Elderly program was established during the COVID-19 pandemic to provide food distribution services. Minarys Dream Alliance serves approximately 50 percent of the Kent County senior population living in poverty. Kent County has pledged funding to support this program through the next three years. This food distribution program will continue to provide essential services through the next three years with this funding.

borrower_name: ROCK HALL VOLUNTEER FIRE COMPANY, INC.
funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
naics_description: RESCUE AND AMBULANCE SERVICE - EQUIPMENT BUILDING
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a 36 foot Aluminum Fire and Safety Rescue Vessel for the Rock Hall Volunteer Fire Company (RCVFC). This commercial grade fire boat will assist in protecting the marinas, waterfront properties, and Rock Hall boating community. Currently, Rock Hall must rely on equipment from other areas, such as the Kent Island fireboat, which travels nearly 15 miles (30 minutes) to assist with fires. RHVFC responds to over 200 fire/rescue calls annually and more than 500 emergency medical services related calls. The coverage extends more than 130 square miles. RHVFC is "first call" emergency medical, fire and rescue services to the towns of Betterton, Chestertown, Galena, Kennedyville, Millington, and an integral part of the Kent and Queen Annes counties rescue squad. The purchase of the upgraded fire and safety vessel will result in improved public safety, prevent the loss of life and property, and preserve the ecosystem and environment.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a hybrid law enforcement vehicle. The town of Cottage City has decided to "Go Green". They are reducing their carbon footprint by replacing an older fossil fuel vehicle with a Hybrid vehicle. The new vehicle will be replacing the currently used gas powered vehicle. The town of Cottage City has decided on purchasing a hybrid vehicle because they are better on the environment, fuel efficient, and have lower operating cost; all beneficial to the town. This investment is the start of a future plan for the town; having the entire police fleet of vehicle be hybrid. The town receives a heavy amount of traffic due to its neighboring city, Washington D. C. The funding of this upgraded equipment will benefit this town in allowing it to continue to provide excellent service and maintain a safe and secure community.

program: Rural Energy for America Program Renewable Energy Systems and Energy Efficiency Improvement Loans and Grants
funding_code: REAP-MANDATORY RENEW ENERGY SYST GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development Investment will be used to help Ideal Farms purchase and install a 504 kilowatt (kW) ground mounted solar system. Ideal Farms is a family-owned poultry farm in Marion Station, Maryland. The new system is expected to save the eight poultry house farm $43,407 in electrical costs per year. It will replace 668,198 kilowatt hours (kWh) (107.76 percent of the companys energy use) per year, which is enough energy to power 61 homes.

funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase two hybrid Ford Interceptors for the city of Crisfields Law Enforcement Department. This purchase will include additional equipment outfitted on the vehicles. The two older vehicles currently in use are more than a decade old and have some major safety issues, including transmission issues, engine trouble, hanging wires, and rust throughout the undercarriage. Crisfield is concerned about its passengers and the fluctuating cost of gasoline. The city of Crisfield has requested this funding to replace its old vehicles with safer, more gas efficient vehicles. The population of Crisfield is 2,756 and the Median Household Income (MHI) is $39,046, which is 49% of the State Non-metropolitan median household income.

funding_code: (GRANT ONLY) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide additional funding for the Smith Island Waste Water Treatment Plant (WWTP) Improvements project. This project has been designed in four phases. This phase will provide an enhanced nutrient removal system for the entire island by replacing all of the degraded equipment with equipment better suited for the unique island conditions. The project will eliminate unsanitary sewer discharges into the Tangier Sound and Chesapeake Bay. This project will benefit both the environment and the population of Smith Island as it will increase climate and coastal resiliency and increase assurance of access to sanitary sewer services for the island residents and businesses, so they may maintain their unique way of life.

funding_code: DISCRETION RURAL MICROPENTERPR DEV ORG
naics_industry_sector: Other Services (except Public Administration) (81)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide business based training and technical assistance to rural microenterprises and microentrepreneurs on the Eastern Shore of Maryland. As a participating microlender, grant funds are made available to Eastern Shore entrepreneurship Center annually based on lending activity and the availability of funding. Previous grant funds have supported this project, and been matched with at least 15 percent from Eastern Shore Entrepreneurship Center.

funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
naics_description: CONTINUING CARE RETIREMENT COMMUNITIES AND ASSISTED LIVING FACILITIES FOR THE ELDERLY
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist with the installation of heating, ventilation and air conditioning systems, fencing and furnishings/equipment for their existing pre-school classrooms at Easton Elementary School. Critchlow Adkins Childrens Centers (CACC) are non-profit, educationally based childcare centers that are licensed and accredited through the Maryland State Department of Education. Their mission is to provide quality, financially accessible childcare in a nurturing, diverse, safe, and enriching environment. CACC works in partnership with Talbot County Public Schools (TCPS) by providing educational year-round preschool, pre-k - 5th grade before- and after-school care, and summer programs at each of the five area elementary schools which keeps childcare convenient and affordable. The pre-school is located in the town of Easton, Maryland.

project_name: St. Michaels Wastewater Collection System Improvements
funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide additional funding to improve the St. Michaels wastewater collection system. The project will expand on the initial construction area to continue to replace part of the sewer collection system and rehabilitate sections of the sewer system where the structural integrity of the pipe remains in St. Michaels. These improvements will reduce the inflow and infiltration the county is experiencing with the existing St. Michaels sewer system service area.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to improve the quality and quantity of drinking water for the 651 residents of the Town of Oxford, in Talbot County, MD. The Water System Improvement project includes the replacement of aging water mains, meters, and communication systems, as well as the rehabilitation of the towns water treatment system. Construction is expected to take two years and will result in enhanced treatment for arsenic and fluoride, more efficient communication and billing, and increased water flow necessary for emergency response.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to support the economic recovery for Brook Lane Health Services Inc. from the financial impact of COVID-19. Brook Lane Health Services provides various forms of psychotherapy, substance abuse therapy, outpatient therapy, psychiatric, and inpatient services for both children and adults. This organization has four locations, including Hagerstown, Laurel Hall, and two facilities in Frederick, Maryland. Over the last three years of the COVID-19 pandemic, Brook Lane Health Services was forced to shut down some of their inpatient beds to reduce the spread of COVID within their facility. This investment will replace a portion of the health care related lost revenue. Brook Lane Health Services is located outside of the incorporated limits of Hagerstown, Maryland.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a passenger van to assist with emergency food and transportation programs. Interfaith Service Coalition of Hancock, Maryland Inc. (ISC) is located in Washington County, MD, a designated disaster county. Since the beginning of the COVID-19 pandemic, ISC has delivered meals to senior citizens and individuals within Hancock, MD with compromised immune systems who are apprehensive to leave their homes. ISC also works with local fire companies, rescue squads, and police departments to provide meals, transportation, any anything else within reason that is needed during times of emergency. The requested van is essential to keep ISCs emergency food and transportation programs in operation to continue serving the people of Washington County, Hancock, MD.

The proposed stormwater management project will improve water quality and help to correct a health and sanitary problem in this impaired watershed by preventing soil erosion, minimizing pollutants in stormwater runoff, increasing groundwater recharge, and protecting downstream receiving channels from stormwater pollutants. funding_code: REAP-MANDATORY RENEW ENERGY SYST GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development Investment will be used to help purchase and install a 679.5 kilowatt (kW) ground mounted solar system. Aksmah,LLC is a family-owned poultry farm in Pocomoke City, Maryland. The new system is expected to save the nineteen poultry house farm $73,9717 in electrical costs per year. It will replace 896,877 kilowatt hours (kWh) (107.91 percent of the companys energy use) per year, which is enough energy to power 82 homes.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
naics_description: RESCUE AND AMBULANCE SERVICE - EQUIPMENT BUILDING
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase an ambulance for Pocomoke City that will improve access to emergency medical services during the surge of the COVID-19 pandemic. This new ambulance will replace an older vehicle that is lacking many safety and health standards critical to COVID safety, including better air filtration with heating, ventilation and air conditioning comprehensive air disinfection, and a power lift system for administering oxygen. The need to increase safety during medical emergencies is especially important to the vulnerable populations of Pocomoke City. As of the 2019 Census, data shows that Pocomoke City is comprised of nearly 51 percent minority populations, and approximately 22 percent of the population is living in poverty. These features are not only important to the patients, but also to the crew maneuvering the equipment. Pocomoke City reported that more than 50% of their EMS personnel contracted COVID over the last two years. With these factors in mind, this funding is imperative to the health and safety of Pocomoke City.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help L. Henry Maier farm purchase and install new 15 kW replacement blades and motor for an existing wind turbine. L. Henry Maier operates a horse and timber farm in Oldtown, Maryland. The new system is expected to save the farm $1,416 per year in electrical costs.

funding_code: FY22 CONGRESSIONALLY DIRECTED SPENDING
naics_industry_sector: Educational Services (61)
naics_description: ALL OTHER MISCELLANEOUS SCHOOLS AND INSTRUCTION
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to renovate the community theatre in the Allegany College of Maryland Center. The space has been untouched since the 1970s and physical infrastructure is beginning to fail. This project will help to revitalize the space and bring it up to all codes and standards. With this investment, the theatre aims to increase community patron usage and add state of-the-art upgraded equipment that benefits both the community and the colleges Multimedia Technology program. Allegany College of Maryland, located in Cumberland, Maryland, is continuously adapting and modernizing to fit the needs of their students and the community members. The renovations of this theater will benefit them by allowing more college events and workforce trainings, as well as allowing the public to utilize the space for performances.

funding_code: CY 2022  REGULAR GRANTS DIV N
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to refurbish an 18-year-old Ladder Truck consisting of painting and potential mechanical upgrades being used by the organization. The current equipment is dated and in need of enhancements and some mechanical upgrades. The age of the vehicle is why enhancements are preferred over a new vehicle. The proposed enhancements are needed to extend the usefulness of current equipment and contribute to the towns ability to respond to members of the service area. The primary service area is Allegany and Garrett counties. The population to be served by the proposed service area is 105,184.

funding_code: CY 2022  REGULAR GRANTS DIV N
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase an ambulance. The ambulance will provide advanced life support and the vehicle would be a 4x4 to allow for geographical terrain of mountainous Maryland and Pennsylvania. The primary service area is Allegany County, Maryland and Bedford and Fulton counties in Pennsylvania. The population to be served by the proposed service area is 139,694.

naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)

Specifically, the equipment includes an automatic chest compression system, a positive pressure ventilation fan used to push smoke from a structure and three new hose nozzles. The Orleans Volunteer Fire Company Inc. is located in Allegany County, Maryland with a population of 3,297.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to increase food distribution efforts on the Maryland Eastern Shore by partnering with Chesapeake Culinary Center for the establishment of Eastern Shore Delmarva Farm to Freezer project, a produce processing and aggregation facility. The facility will occupy 5,000 square feet, with half the space used for processing and individual quick frozen equipment and the other half set aside for refrigerated, freezer, and dry storage and staging for shipping and receiving. The community served by this project includes several counties on the Eastern Shore - Caroline, Dorchester, Kent, Queen Annes, Somerset, Talbot, Wicomico, and Worcester - where the estimated poverty rate is more than 13 percent and access to nutritious food is limited.

The project will also replace the Modified Ludzack-Ettinger (MLE) treatment process system with the Simultaneous Nitrification and Denitrification (SNDN) process in the wastewater treatment Modules No. 1 and expand the treatment process reactor to where the equalization and digester reactors are in the current layout. The town of La Plata has a Census 2010 population of 8,753 and a 2006-2010 American Community Survey and MHI of $80,129.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to relocate and drill two new wells and construct a new Water Treatment Plant (WTP), for the Town of Vienna; located in rural Dorchester County, Maryland. The WTP will be equipped with modern controls, treatment, and filtration equipment. The project will also include abandonment of the existing wells, lines, and water treatment building, removal of the existing sludge, and reclamation of the site. The project will benefit residents and the environment alike by facilitating reasonable and planned growth in the area and improving water quality. Total project funding is being provided jointly through the Maryland Department of the Environment.

funding_code: (GRANT ONLY) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to build a new sanitary sewage pumping station on Creamery Road to replace the aging pump station located on the same parcel of land. The pump station has reached the end of its useful life and is no longer able to handle the flow of the system, which is causing multiple Sanitary Sewer Overflows over the last several years which impacts the nearby Toms Creek and Monocacy River causing risk to public health and safety. Overflows have been documented by the local health department and if not corrected, the town runs the risk of being in violation of State mandates. The new pump station will bring the overflows within an allowable limit or eliminate the risk all together.

The grant funds will be used to pay for a marketing campaign to establish M3 Collectives initial sales channels, reach new retail and food service customers, and to assist the business in growing its ground beef production. The business is projected to gain 64 retail and food service customers and increase revenues by $739,000 through the grant period.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to complete sewer system improvements to the Grantsville sewer system including addressing infiltration and inflow and will work to address spikes in flow which correspond with rain events. Funding also includes the completion of a full inflow/infiltration (I/I) study consisting of flow monitoring, detailed manhole inspections, manhole monitoring during rain events, smoke testing and CCTV. The Grantsville sewer system serves the town of Grantsville and an area in Garrett County. Initial funding for the completion of the Preliminary Engineering Report and Environmental Reporting reviews were completed through funding provided by a SEARCH Grant. Additional funding will fund a small shortfall encountered when the bids came in somewhat above budget.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase an ambulance and equipment for the Galena Volunteer Fire Company (VFC) fleet of emergency vehicles. The need to purchase a newer ambulance with updated equipment has become a noticeable concern for Galena VFC as the COVID-19 pandemic progressed throughout the last three years. Galena VFC is seeking to replace the third ambulance in its fleet. This ambulance is 20 years old and experiencing reliability issues with constant costly repairs. The vehicle has also accumulated more than 110,000 miles and does not meet current COVID-19 safety standards for ambulances. Galena VFC serves the municipal boundaries of six rural town in Maryland: Galena, Kennedyville, Millington, Betterton, Cecilton, and Georgetown.

borrower_name: ROCK HALL VOLUNTEER FIRE COMPANY, INC.
funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase an ambulance and equipment for Rock Hall Volunteer Fire Company (VFC). This new ambulance will replace a sixteen-year-old ambulance that is obsolete, requires too many repairs, and does not meet the modern safety standards required for safety against spreading COVID-19. Rock Hall VFC is the only access to emergency services in the region, and there are no practicing physicians or nurses in the rural town. Many patients need to be transported to larger cities in Maryland, like Chestertown, Annapolis, or Baltimore. This created a capacity issue during the COVID-19 Pandemic with the rise in emergency calls.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to develop a model Master Composter training program for composting foods scraps at community gardens and on farms, both urban and rural. naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a 2023 hybrid police vehicle. The town of Cottage City has decided to "Go Green" and reduce their carbon footprint. Part of the towns "Go Green" plan is to eventually have an entire police fleet of hybrid vehicles. The first step is to replace an older fossil fuel vehicle with a hybrid vehicle because they are better for the environment, more fuel efficient, and have lower operating costs; all beneficial to the town. The town receives a heavy amount of traffic due to its neighboring city, Washington D.C. This project will allow the town to continue providing excellent service and help maintain a safe and secure community. The town of Cottage City received previous Community Facilities grant funds in the amount of $39,500.

funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to improve drinking water quality for customers of the Pocomoke City, Maryland, water system; located in rural Worcester County. The project will install water tank mixing equipment at both City water towers to remove unsafe Trihalomethane chemicals and reduce or eliminate the buildup of bio films and disinfection products in the drinking water. Pocomoke City is considered a socially vulnerable, distressed community, and has a high poverty rate. A grant from the Maryland Department of the Environment is providing the majority of funding for this critical infrastructure project. A low interest loan would allow the proposed project to be fully funded and move forward with construction and correction of this compliance issue. Once completed, the project will ensure healthier, safer, and better tasting water for years to come.

funding_code: (GRANT ONLY) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide additional funding for construction for the Smith Island wastewater treatment plant improvements project, located in rural Somerset County. This project design includes four phases, and the Sanitary District has applied for funding from various federal and state sources to fully fund this critical need. The project will provide an enhanced nutrient removal system for the entire island by consolidating and replacing all of the degraded and failing equipment with equipment more suited for the unique island conditions. The project will eliminate unsanitary sewer discharges into the Tangier Sound and Chesapeake Bay, thus safeguarding sensitive biological resources. Smith Island is identified as a "Distressed Community" and this project aids Rural Developments key priorities to reduce pollution and increase resilience to the impacts of climate change through economic support. The environment and the Smith Island community would benefit from this project as it would further increase climate and coastal resiliency and increase assurance of access to sanitary sewer services for the island residents and businesses, so they may maintain a quality way of life.

funding_code: CY 2022  REGULAR GRANTS DIV N
naics_industry_sector: Information (51)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to support the cost of purchasing a book locker kiosk for the Wicomico County Free Library. The book locker kiosk will be positioned in front of the Westside Community Center in Bivalve, Maryland. The book locker provides 24-hour access to library services for those who may be prevented from traveling to the main library or the branches. Bivalve is more than 18 miles from the nearest branch of the Wicomico County Free Library with limited access to public services. Wicomico County Free Library was awarded 75 percent of the total project in grant funding, and they will cover 25 percent from their own resources.

funding_code: CY 2022  REGULAR GRANTS DIV N
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a law enforcement truck, trailer and accessories for the city of Fruitland, Maryland. This funding will provide 55 percent towards the total project cost, and the city of Fruitland will cover the additional 45 percent costs. The city of Fruitlands Law Enforcement Department currently has no vehicles to support community protection at town events. This police truck and trailer will support the city of Fruitlands efforts to foster engagement with their residents at local events. The citys goal is to lower crime occurrences and encourage safer environments during local events in the community.

project_name: 2023 St. Martins by the Bay Water
funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to extend water service to the St. Martins by the Bay subdivision, located in rural Worcester County, Maryland. The proposed project would extend the existing Ocean Pines water service area to serve the 58 households in the St. Martins subdivision. The subdivision is a coastal community which is at, or less than, 10 feet above sea level. Land subsidence and climate change effects, such as sea-level rise and flooding, are a concern for this vulnerable area. The project would help to mitigate the susceptibility of well contamination from brackish, or saltwater intrusion, by removing the communitys water source away from this low-lying area. In addition, the proposed project would ensure access to safe, reliable drinking water for residents that are currently relying on water from a system that is past its useful life and experiencing failures. The proposed project would connect the subdivision to the Ocean Pines facility at the intersection of St. Martins Lane and Beauchamp Road. All proposed work would be within existing county rights-of-ways. The resulting project would also increase public safety by providing fire flow protection, redundancy, and emergency power to the area for continuous service.

borrower_name: TALBOT COUNTY FREE LIBRARY ASSOCIATION, INC
funding_code: FY22 CONGRESSIONALLY DIRECTED SPENDING
naics_industry_sector: Educational Services (61)
naics_description: ALL OTHER MISCELLANEOUS SCHOOLS AND INSTRUCTION
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to support the design phase for the expansion and renovation of the St. Michaels Library located in Talbot County, Maryland. This investment will assist Talbot County Free Library Association Inc. in preparing for the construction phase anticipated to begin July 2024. The funding of the design prepares for the future facilities expansion and renovation of the current library from 3,071 square feet to increase into a fully functional 10,787 square foot library. The upgrading adds additional study and meeting rooms, children and teen areas, upgraded lighting, seating, and storage, as well as needed maintenance to ensure stability. Talbot County has a population of 37,782. Upgrading the current space will increase program attendance by 30 percent.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to support the purchase of equipment, minor construction on the exterior and interior upgrades to the Hancock Fire Company fire station. The equipment will include hoses, a thermal camera, lights, batteries, chargers, gas detector, and eight storage drawer beds. The minor interior construction will include installation of new flooring and panel partitions inserted to create private small rooms for firefighters. The minor exterior construction will include new shutters and gutters on the exterior of the facility. This equipment and facility upgrades will help Hancock Fire Company with disaster readiness. This organization was a first responder in Washington County, Maryland to the disasters caused by the 2018 and 2019 Hurricanes Michael and Florence. According to the 2020 Decennial Census, the population of Hancock, Maryland is 1,557.

borrower_name: INTERFAITH SERVICE COALITION OF HANCOCK, MD, INC.
funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to support the costs of appliances, equipment, exterior improvements, and installation/labor costs of the upgrades for the Good Samaritan House. Interfaith Service Coalition is an eligible and rural nonprofit organization that owns and operates the Good Samaritan House, located in Hancock, Maryland. The Good Samaritan House serves disaster victims that may be displaced due to fire, flood, death in the family or other devastating circumstances. This organization provided transitional housing services to those who suffered in Washington County due to the 2018 and 2019 Hurricanes Michael and Florence disasters. The Good Samaritan House suffered some exterior damage from the 2018/2019 Hurricane disasters and Interfaith Service Coalition has not yet had the resources to recover and upgrade the facility. Additionally, most of their appliances and are more than 15 years old and need to be replaced for disaster readiness. According to the 2020 Decennial Census, the population of Hancock, Maryland is 1,557.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to support the purchase of a National Fire Protection Association (NFPA) compliant Class A custom built engine tanker. The Sharpsburg Volunteer Fire Company Inc. (SVFC) is a non-profit corporation providing fire and rescue service for Sharpsburg and Washington counties. The apparatus specified in this request will replace the existing outdated, substandard, unreliable, and unsafe equipment currently used by personnel to protect their community. This project is located in Washington County, Maryland and their service area is part of the disaster designation FEMA-4374-DR, Maryland Disaster Declaration as of 6/25/2018, Maryland Severe Storms and Flooding.
